'''Curriki''' is an online, free, open education service.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pratt|first=Mary|title=Online community lets educators, students share educational resources for free|url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9227460/Online_community_lets_educators_students_share_educational_resources_for_free|publisher=ComputerWorld|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref> Curriki is structured as a [[nonprofit organization]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/01/technology/01ping.html|title=Ping - In School Systems, Slow Progress for Open-Source Textbooks - NYTimes.com|last=Vance|first=Ashlee|access-date=2017-11-02}}</ref> to provide [[open educational resources]] primarily in support of [[K-12]] education.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vance|first=Ashlee|title=$200 Textbook vs. Free. You Do the Math.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/01/technology/01ping.html|accessdate=27 September 2012|newspaper=NY Times|date=31 July 2010}}</ref> Curricula and instructional materials are available at the Curriki website to teachers, professional educators, students, lifelong learners, and parents. The majority of the resources on the Curriki site fall under a [[Creative Commons]] license.<ref>{{cite web|last=Park|first=Jane|title=CC Talks With: Curriki’s Christine Mytko: Open Education and Policy|url=https://creativecommons.org/tag/curriki|publisher=Creative Commons|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref> Educational materials are provided by the Curriki community and are peer-reviewed for quality and adherence to standards.
The name Curriki is a [[portmanteau]] of the words "curriculum" and "wiki".{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}
Curriki's model is to develop curricula through community contributors, and to deliver curricula and open educational resources globally. Anyone with access to the Internet can contribute and use the material found on Curriki to teach themselves or others. Since the materials, which include digital textbooks, learning videos, and interactive resources, are provided in open source, they can be adapted as needed to particular requirements inside or outside of the classroom.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
==History== Curriki was founded by [[Sun Microsystems]] in March 2004 as the Global Education & Learning Community (GELC). In 2006, Sun spun GELC off as an independent 501(c)(3) nonprofit to focus on building a repository of curricula and to create an online community for this repository. The organization changed its name to Curriki in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.findlaw.com/wash/s/20071102/200711021733441.html|title=Web Site Offers Global Collaboration on Educational Resources|website=news.findlaw.com|access-date=2017-11-02}}</ref>
Curriki has over 350,000 educator, parent, and student members, and has garnered over 8.5 million visits from around the world. Curriki has received a number of awards, and has also given out a number of awards over the past several years; a partial list can be found at the Curriki website. [[Kim Jones (Sun)|Kim Jones]] serves as Curriki's CEO.
In September 2017, Curriki partnered with AT&T in order to come up with interactive [[Mathematics|math]] assessments tools, with which students would be given real-time feedback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thejournal.com/articles/2017/09/27/curriki-launches-realtime-math-assessments-for-students-in-grades-812.aspx|title=Curriki Launches Real-Time Math Assessments for Students in Grades 8-12 -- THE Journal|website=THE Journal|language=en|access-date=2017-11-02}}</ref>
